<ce:para>This paper presents a new strategy for simulation of thermally coupled distillation sequences using process simulators. First, we show that the two side streams connections that produce a 'thermal couple' can be accurately substituted by a combination of a material stream and a heat flow. In this way, the sequence of thermally coupled distillation columns can be simulated without recycle streams like any conventional simulation of zeotropic distillation sequences. In that way a sequence of thermally coupled distillation columns is as difficult to converge as any other distillation system without recycles. In most situations this approach introduces negligible errors, but in any case provides excellent initial points to the rigorous simulations with recycle streams. Different examples are presented, including mixtures of hydrocarbons (C4's -C5'sC6's), aromatics (BTX), alcohols, non-ideal azeotropic systems (acetone, benzene,chloroform)and systems involving 4 or 5 components. Different thermodynamic equivalent configurations that correspond to different alternatives for implementing this approach are also described. © 2011 Elsevier B.V.</ce:para>
